|Minister for Housing]] [[Eoghan Murphy]] was defeated in the D\u00e1il by 59 votes to 49 votes with 29 abstentions.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/minister-for-housing-eoghan-murphy-survives-motion-of-no-confidence-vote-871456.html Minister for Housing Eoghan Murphy survives motion of no confidence vote], Irish Examiner, 2018-09-25.</ref>\n* 26 September \n** The deadline for nominations to contest the Presidential Election passed.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2018/0926/998175-presidential-election/ Deadline for Presidential nominations passes], RT\u00c9 News, 2018-09-26.</ref>\n** 18-year-old student Rebecca Carter, who was in danger of losing her university place after the marks on one of her Leaving Certificate papers were incorrectly added up, won her case against the State Examinations Commission in the High Court.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/courts/2018/0926/998235-leaving-cert/  Student wins case over incorrect Leaving Cert marks], RT\u00c9 News, 2018-09-26.</ref>\n* 27 September \u2013 A man who was late for a flight to [[Amsterdam]] was pinned down by Ryanair staff and police after running out of the Dublin Airport terminal onto the tarmac.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/man-tackled-to-the-tarmac-by-dublin-airport-staff-after-storming-onto-apron-to-make-amsterdam-flight-37359902.html Man tackled to the tarmac by Dublin Airport staff after storming onto apron to make Amsterdam flight], Irish Independent, 2018-09-27.</ref>\n* 30 September \u2013 The bodies of three men were recovered from the water close to their upturned rib near Coonanna in [[County Kerry|South Kerry]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/three-bodies-recovered-from-water-off-kerry-coast-872546.html Update: Bodies of three men recovered from water off Kerry coast], Irish Examiner, 2018-09-30.</ref>\n\n===October===\n<!-- PLEASE PROVIDE PROPER CITATIONS FOR ALL ITEMS ADDED -->\n* 1 October \n** Twelve people were arrested as part of an ongoing Garda investigation into child abuse.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2018/1001/999305-arrests/ 12 arrested in child abuse investigation] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-01.</ref> \n** Fine Gael TD [[Peter Fitzpatrick]] resigned from the party and announced his intention to run in the next election as an independent candidate.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/louth-td-peter-fitzpatrick-resigns-from-fine-gael-party-1.3648207 Louth TD Peter Fitzpatrick resigns from Fine Gael party] Irish Times, 2018-10-01.</ref> \n* 2 October \n** DUP leader Arlene Foster said the [[Good Friday Agreement]] should not be considered as a sacrosanct piece of legislation in Brexit negotiations.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/brexit-arlene-foster-says-belfast-agreement-is-not-untouchable-1.3648709 Brexit: Arlene Foster says Belfast Agreement is not untouchable] Irish Times, 2018-10-02.</ref> \n** Flights in and out of [[Cork Airport|Cork]], Shannon and [[Knock Airport|Knock]] airports were temporarily suspended due to \"significant air traffic issues\" regarding the radar system at Shannon.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-airspace-closed-with-immediate-effect-due-to-significant-radar-failure-37378752.html Irish airspace 'closed with immediate effect' due to 'significant radar failure'] Irish Independent, 2018-10-02.</ref> \n* 3 October\n** Thousands of people from around the country took part in the Raise the Roof protest in Dublin to highlight the housing crisis.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/thousands-protest-at-raise-the-roof-rally-as-taoiseach-defends-housing-policy-in-dail-873200.html Government defends housing record as over 10,000 take to streets in protest] Irish Examiner, 2018-10-03.</ref> \n** Minister for Housing [[Eoghan Murphy]] acknowledged there is a \"serious crisis\" in housing as the D\u00e1il debated a private members' motion on the issue.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2018/1003/1000687-dail-housing/ Minister acknowledges 'serious crisis' in housing] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-03.</ref> \n** The Public Health (Alcohol) Bill, which was before the [[Oireachtas]] since 2015, was passed. It will mean more stringent rules around the sale of alcohol.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2018/1003/1000785-alcohol-bill/ Alcohol Bill passes D\u00e1il after more than 1,000 days] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-03.</ref>\n[[File:Howth Castle and Environs.jpg|thumb|Howth Castle sold after 840 years.]]\n* 4 October\n** The Minister for Health introduced the [[Health (Regulation of Termination of Pregnancy) Bill 2018|Regulation of the Termination of Pregnancy Bill]] in the [[D\u00e1il]] to legalise abortion services in Ireland.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2018/1004/1000958-abortion/ Bill to legalise abortion services introduced in D\u00e1il] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-04.</ref>\n** The government lost a D\u00e1il vote by 83 votes to 43 on a motion tabled by [[Solidarity-People Before Profit]] to declare housing and homelessness a national emergency.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2018/1004/1000866-housing-crisis/ Government loses vote on D\u00e1il housing motion] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-04.</ref>\n** The Office of the President announced that it will be handing around \u20ac200,000 back to the State from the underspend of the Presidential allowance.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/president-to-return-200000-in-unspent-allowance-after-seven-year-term-873561.html President to return \u20ac200,000 in unspent allowance after seven-year term] Irish Examiner, 2018-10-04.</ref>\n** The Saint Lawrence family, which has owned [[Howth Castle]] and its 182-hectare (450-acre) desmesne for more than 840 years, announced their agreement to sell the property to an investment group.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/business/commercial-property/tetrarch-buys-470-acres-in-howth-including-its-castle-and-former-hotel-1.3651989 Tetrarch buys 470 acres in Howth including its castle and former hotel] Irish Times, 2018-10-05.</ref>\n* 5 October \u2013 Father-of-two Robert Sheridan was shot dead after he answered the door at his home at Poppintree Crescent in [[Ballymun]] at around 11.15pm.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/fatheroftwo-45-dead-following-shooting-in-north-dublin-named-locally-37390435.html Father-of-two (45) dead following shooting in north Dublin named locally] Irish Independent, 2018-10-06.</ref>\n* 6 October \u2013 Conor McGregor submitted to [[Khabib Nurmagomedov]] during [[UFC 229|a fight]] in [[Paradise, Nevada]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/oct/07/khabib-conor-mcgregor-fight-crowd-brawl-report Khabib Nurmagomedov taps out Conor McGregor then sparks melee in crowd] The Guardian, 2018-10-07.</ref>\n* 8 October \u2013 A murder investigation was launched after a 44-year-old man was found dead with suspected stab wounds and two other people were injured in [[Macroom]].<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/man-dies-two-injured-in-cork-stabbing-874305.html Latest: Man fatally stabbed in Cork named locally as Timmy Foley] Irish Examiner, 2018-10-08.</ref>\n* 9 October \u2013 The Minister for Finance, [[Paschal Donohoe]], announced the [[Irish budget, 2019|2019 Budget]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/budget19-live-the-main-points-from-todays-budget-874633.html |title =Budget19: A summary of the main points|date=9 October 2017|work=Irish Examiner|accessdate=10 October 2018}}</ref>\n* 10 October\n** The funeral mass of Emma Mhic Mhath\u00fana took place at the [[St Mary's Pro-Cathedral|Pro-Cathedral]] in Dublin. Her funeral cort\u00e8ge later passed by [[Leinster House]], [[Government Buildings]], and [[\u00c1ras an Uachtar\u00e1in]].<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/hundreds-line-dublin-s-streets-for-emma-mhic-mhath%C3%BAna-cortege-1.3658553 Hundreds line Dublin's streets for Emma Mhic Mhath\u00fana cortege] Irish Times, 2018-10-10.</ref>\n** The Public Health (Alcohol) Bill was signed by the President. It will see cancer warnings on labels (a development vigorously opposed by the alcohol industry),and the introduction of minimum pricing to prohibit cheap selling, and the regulation of alcohol marketing and advertising.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2018/1010/1002310-alcohol-bill/ Alcohol Bill passes all stages of Oireachtas] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-10.</ref>\n* 11 October\n** [[Denis Naughten]] resigned as [[Minister for Communications, Climate Action and Environment|Minister for Communications]] over revelations he met three times with the only bidder still in the national broadband plan process.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/denis-naughten-resigns-as-minister-for-communications-875172.html|title =Denis Naughten resigns as Communications Minister after broadband controversy|date=11 October 2018|publisher=Irish Examiner|accessdate=11 October 2018}}</ref>\n** The third interim report of the [[Garda whistleblower scandal#Disclosures Tribunal|Disclosures Tribunal]] vindicated Garda Sergeant Maurice McCabe, former Garda Commissioner N\u00f3ir\u00edn O'Sullivan, and former Minister for Justice [[Frances Fitzgerald (politician)|Frances Fitzgerald]]; it severely criticised former Garda Commissioner [[Martin Callinan]] and former Garda press officer Superintendent David Taylor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2018/1011/1002470-disclosures-tribunal-dave-taylor/|title='Utter mystery' as to how Taylor was press officer, says Charleton|publisher=RT\u00c9|date=11 October 2018|access-date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n* 12 October  \n** [[Iarnr\u00f3d \u00c9ireann]] introduced a ban on alcohol on a number of Friday services to [[Galway]] and [[Westport, County Mayo|Westport]].<ref>[https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/irish-rail-may-ban-alcohol-on-more-services-875369.html Irish Rail may ban alcohol on more services] Breaking News, 2018-10-12.</ref>\n** ''[[The Late Late Show (Irish TV series)|The Late Late Show]]'' was broadcast from the [[Methodist Central Hall, Westminster|Central Hall]] in [[London]]. It was the third time since 1968 that the show travelled to London.<ref>[https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/late-late-show-london-special-a-glorified-town-hall-shindig-1.3662862 Late Late Show London special: A glorified town-hall shindig] Irish Times, 2018-10-12.</ref>\n* 13 October \u2013 [[Richard Bruton]] was named as Minister for Communications while [[Joe McHugh]] was nominated as [[Minister for Education and Skills]].<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2018/1013/1002915-minister-appointments/ Bruton named Minister for Communications, McHugh named Minister for Education] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-13.</ref>\n* 14 October \u2013 Former Garda press officer, Superintendent Dave Taylor, applied to retire early from the Garda\u00ed the day after being suspended from the force.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/disgraced-garda-supt-david-taylor-set-to-retire-on-full-pension-37418394.html Disgraced Garda Supt David Taylor set to retire on full pension] Irish Independent, 2018-10-14.</ref>\n* 15 October \u2013 DUP leader Arlene Foster visited Dublin for talks with the Taoiseach and the Fianna F\u00e1il leader, Miche\u00e1l Martin.<ref>[https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/arlene-foster-and-leo-varadkar-deadlocked-over-backstop-876023.html Arlene Foster and Leo Varadkar deadlocked over backstop] Irish Examiner, 2018-10-15.</ref>\n* 16 October \u2013 119 Irish soldiers deployed to the [[Golan Heights]] and [[Syria]] returned home following a two-week delay due to diplomatic clearance.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2018/1016/1003506-irish-troops-return/ Wait finally over as Irish troops return from UN duties] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-16.</ref>\n* 18 October \u2013 A 21-year-old Italian man was found not guilty of causing grievous bodily harm to Se\u00e1n Cox outside [[Anfield Stadium]] in [[Liverpool]] earlier this year.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2018/1018/1004957-sean-cox/ Man found not guilty of causing grievous bodily harm to Irish Liverpool fan] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-18.</ref>\n* 19 October \n** National Slow Down day, a 24-hour operation aimed at getting motorists to watch their speed on roads, took place.<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/garda-to-carry-out-speed-checks-in-more-than-1000-areas-as-part-of-national-slow-down-day-37436877.html Garda\u00ed to carry out speed checks in more than 1,000 areas as part of National Slow Down Day] Irish Independent, 2018-10-19.</ref>\n** Presidential candidate Peter Casey temporarily suspended his campaign in light of the controversy over his earlier comments about [[Irish travellers|Travellers]].<ref>[https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/presidential-election-2018/peter-casey-suspends-campaign-for-presidency-following-controversial-traveller-comments-37437133.html Peter Casey suspends campaign for presidency following controversial Traveller comments] Irish Independent, 2018-10-19.</ref>\n* 21 October \n** Ardgillan Community College in [[Balbriggan]] was forced to close down a section of its building after significant structural flaws were discovered following a fire safety audit.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/education/2018/1021/1005655-balbriggan-school-dublin/ Section of school building closed in Dublin after structural flaws discovered] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-21.</ref>\n** Presidential candidate Peter Casey announced that he intended to resume his campaign after suspending it for 48 hours.<ref>[https://www.rte.ie/news/2018/1021/1005647-peter-casey-presidential-election/ Peter Casey to remain in the race for \u00c1ras an Uachtar\u00e1in] RT\u00c9 News, 2018-10-21.</ref>\n* 23 October \u2013 It was announced that two Dublin primary schools with a combined enrolment of 1,200 are to close immediately following structural assessment inspections.<ref>